## Domain Configuration — IONOS

> **WARNING:** Do NOT change the NS records for **{{ domain }}** itself.
> The registrar must remain the authoritative nameserver for the base domain.
> Changing the base NS records will break email delivery (MX, SPF, DMARC).
>
> You are only delegating the **prod.{{ domain }}** subdomain to your home DNS servers.
>
> **Do NOT go to the "Nameserver" tab** — that changes the NS for the whole domain.
> Stay in the **DNS** tab to add individual records.

### Subdomain Delegation

- [ ] Log into IONOS at [{{ platforms.registrar.url }}]({{ platforms.registrar.url }})
- [ ] Navigate to **Domains & SSL** → **{{ domain }}** → **DNS**

Add the A records first, then the NS records. Some registrars validate that the
nameserver hostname resolves before accepting the NS record.

{# In the IONOS DNS editor, the "Hostname" field is relative to the domain,
   so entering "dns1" creates dns1.{{ domain }}. For NS "Points to" fields,
   the fully qualified hostname is required: dns1.{{ domain }}. #}

> **IONOS note:** In the DNS editor, the "Hostname" field is relative to `{{ domain }}`.
> Enter `dns1` to create `dns1.{{ domain }}`. For NS record "Points to" fields,
> enter the fully qualified name: `dns1.{{ domain }}`.

**Step 1 — A records (create these first):**

| Type | Hostname | Points to |
|------|----------|-----------|
| A | dns1 | {{ public_ip }} |
| A | dns2 | {{ public_ip }} |

- [ ] A record for `dns1.{{ domain }}` → `{{ public_ip }}` created
- [ ] A record for `dns2.{{ domain }}` → `{{ public_ip }}` created

**Step 2 — NS records (create after A records exist):**

| Type | Hostname | Points to |
|------|----------|-----------|
| NS | prod | dns1.{{ domain }} |
| NS | prod | dns2.{{ domain }} |

- [ ] NS record delegating `prod.{{ domain }}` → `dns1.{{ domain }}` created
- [ ] NS record delegating `prod.{{ domain }}` → `dns2.{{ domain }}` created

> **Dev DNS:** The `dev.{{ domain }}` subdomain is intentionally NOT delegated publicly.
> Dev DNS servers are only reachable within the dev VLAN. No registrar configuration
> is needed for dev.

### What Should NOT Be Changed

Verify these are intact after adding the delegation records:

- [ ] MX records for {{ domain }} — unchanged
- [ ] SPF record (TXT) for {{ domain }} — unchanged
- [ ] DMARC record (_dmarc.{{ domain }}) — unchanged
- [ ] No NS records for **{{ domain }}** itself were modified
- [ ] The **Nameserver** tab still shows IONOS default nameservers

### Verification

After records are added (may take minutes to hours to propagate):

```bash
# Verify A records for nameservers
dig A dns1.{{ domain }}
dig A dns2.{{ domain }}
# Expected: {{ public_ip }} for both

# Verify subdomain delegation
dig NS prod.{{ domain }}
# Expected: dns1.{{ domain }}. and dns2.{{ domain }}.

# Verify base domain NS was NOT changed
dig NS {{ domain }}
# Expected: IONOS default nameservers (NOT dns1/dns2.{{ domain }})
```

- [ ] `dig A dns1.{{ domain }}` returns `{{ public_ip }}`
- [ ] `dig A dns2.{{ domain }}` returns `{{ public_ip }}`
- [ ] `dig NS prod.{{ domain }}` returns `dns1.{{ domain }}` and `dns2.{{ domain }}`
- [ ] `dig NS {{ domain }}` still returns IONOS default nameservers
